Dear Friend of Borders,

While going through photo albums over the holidays, I stumbled=20
across a column clipped from my hometown newspaper, dated=20
January 1, 1995. There were photos of several town citizens=20
with captions declaring each person's New Year's resolution. A=20
local real-estate agent wanted to lose 50 pounds by summer. A=20
high-school teacher wanted to spend more time with his own=20
kids. And then there's me, grinning cheekily off the page,=20
announcing, "I don't make resolutions. I'm perfect."=20

That statement was only half true. I had given up on New Year's=20
resolutions not because I honestly believed I was perfect, but=20
because, in my experience, they never worked. Now, a few years=20
older and maybe a little bit wiser, I have learned that a=20
lasting lifestyle overhaul is best built from small,=20
sustainable changes. Take dieting, for instance. I can't live=20
on cabbage soup. I can, however, forego all kinds of packaged=20
grocery-store treats. I'm trying to focus on being well, not=20
skinny. I've been studying THE GOOD FAT COOKBOOK, in which Fran=20
McCullough asks the sensible question, "If we've been eating=20
low-fat for 30 years, why haven't we gotten healthier?" She=20
doesn't suggest easy answers. Instead, she thoroughly explains=20
the difference between bad fats and essential fats, and she=20
offers recipes rich in the latter, like this yummy SALMON CHOWDER.=20

So, what are your goals for 2003? Do you want to get fit? Maybe=20
you're resolved to get your financial house in order. Perhaps=20
you'd like to learn to be happier. Whatever your goals for the=20
year ahead, you'll find a wealth of resources for smart,=20
meaningful change in our NEW YEAR, NEW YOU boutique.=20

And remember: Take it easy.=20

Happy New Year,=20
Jessica Jernigan=20


