<B>FICTION</B><BR>
<B>A NEW YORK STORY</B> -- In <B>Pete Hamill</B>'s <A HREF=3D"http://border=
s1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB7922213127X1733952X151952X">Forever</A>, Cormac O'Conno=
r arrives in New York from Ireland in 1740 and is granted the gift of immor=
tality, provided he never leaves the island of Manhattan. Over the next two=
-and-a-half centuries, O'Connor watches New York evolve from a wilderness i=
nto the city that never sleeps. As he relates in this <A HREF=3D"http://bor=
ders1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB7922213127X1733953X151952X">essay</A>, Hamill finish=
ed his latest novel September 10, 2001. One day later, watching his city bl=
ow apart, he realized he would have to rewrite the end of the book. We meet=
 the boy Cormac in this <A HREF=3D"http://borders1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB7922213=
127X1733954X151952X">excerpt</A>. <BR>
<BR>
<B>URBAN GRIT</B> -- In this <A HREF=3D"http://borders1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB79=
22213127X1733955X151952X">Q&A</A>, Richard Price explains that his latest n=
ovel, <A HREF=3D"http://borders1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB7922213127X1733956X151952=
X">Samaritan</A>, is "about the Haves reaching out without really understan=
ding what the Have Nots are all about, and the trickiness of trying to conn=
ect in a real and meaningful way across the lines of race and class." It's =
also a riveting mystery, a literary blend of psychological suspense and pol=
ice procedural. Protagonist Ray Mitchell tells his teenage daughter a story=
 in this <A HREF=3D"http://borders1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB7922213127X1733957X151=
952X">excerpt</A>. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ART AND LIFE</B> -- Baroque painter Artemisia Gentileschi's sex made her=
 a novelty, a fact that created sensational demand for her work. But her se=
x also made her vulnerable to criticism, and it prevented her from earning =
the reputation and lasting legacy afforded to her male peers. In <A HREF=3D=
"http://borders1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB7922213127X1733958X151952X">The Passion o=
f Artemisia</A> (now available in paperback), <B>Susan Vreeland</B> (<A HRE=
F=3D"http://borders1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB7922213127X1733959X151952X">Girl in H=
yacinth Blue</A>) brings this once-lost artist to light. The author talks a=
bout her heroine in this <A HREF=3D"http://borders1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB792221=
3127X1733960X151952X">interview</A>, and she introduces her in this <A HREF=
=3D"http://borders1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB7922213127X1733961X151952X">excerpt</A=
>. <BR>
<BR>
<B>PENGUIN CLASSICS</B> -- Wouldn't it be nice to say you've read <A HREF=
=3D"http://borders1.m0.net/m/s.asp?HB7922213127X1733962X151952X">Moby-Dick<=
/A> and actually mean it? This year, while you're resolving to reduce your =
body mass index, perhaps you should give your brain a workout, too. When yo=
u buy two selected reissues from Penguin Classics this month at Borders sto=
res, you get a third one free. We've made a <A HREF=3D"http://borders1.m0.n=
et/m/s.asp?HB7922213127X1733963X151952X">list</A> of some of our favorite t=
itles to get you started. <BR>
